      "content": "The strongest philosophical argument is that government censorship inherently corrupts the marketplace of ideas by allowing the state to decide which truths are permissible, effectively turning citizens into subjects rather than free thinkers. When the government acts as the ultimate arbiter of speech, it inevitably creates a chilling effect where individuals self-censor to avoid state retribution, thereby stifling innovation and dissent before it even begins. This approach fundamentally violates the core democratic principle that the truth emerges from open, unfiltered competition, not from a curated list approved by bureaucrats. Ultimately, any regulation that grants the state power to block content is a direct assault on the very concept of liberty that defines a free society.",
